&gt;&gt; video and audio do indeed have a fallback mechanism, and e.g. <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://hacks.mozilla.org/2009/06/html5-video-fallbacks-markup/">http://hacks.mozilla.org/2009/06/html5- ... ks-markup/</a><!-- m --> has an example with &lt;embed&gt; as fallback in &lt;video&gt;.<br /><br />&gt; By the way, feel free to send a summary of this discussion to the whatwg mailing list and propose that &lt;embed&gt; should be obsoleted, <br /><br />Thanks for your inputs. I will. <br /><br />Thnks for the example. I am just about ready to play with that new stuff. <br />I like the structure and source fallback mechanism and I think it shows very well why embed is really not sufficient due to the unknown fallback you can end up with. As some of the comments there, try to use &lt;object&gt; for a deeper and more comprehensive solution to what happens if you can't run your intended video content. May reallly need a fallback to just text that says sorry this video can't play. Also, isn't there the prospect of some intermediate fallback that anly shows when the node is busy getting or preparing content? <br />But if it works that is great and there is plenty or room to develop. <br /><br />Thanks Again and Best Regards, <br />Joe<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=508">joedw</a> — Wed Jun 24, 2009 11:55 pm</p><hr />
