d to send? In &lt;object&gt; they are &lt;param&gt;s. In &lt;embed&gt; they are a quoted string li&gt;ke the old .open. Just mostly uneditable or at least difficult to deal with, that is all.<br /></div></blockquote><br />In &lt;embed&gt; they are normal attributes, where the attribute name is equivalent to &lt;param name=&quot;...&quot;&gt; and the attribute value is equivalent to &lt;param value=&quot;...&quot;&gt;. Maybe we're talking past each other but I don't understand why it's more difficult to deal with.<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>joedw wrote:</cite><br />Here we are discussing a live, scriptable object that may wish to use services via the DOM. &quot;Dead' elements don't count. Really, I don't think &lt;img&gt; has a place in this conversation. I brought it in because the old spec test mentioned it (now changed).<br /></div></blockquote>Ok.<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>joedw wrote:</cite><br />You hinted that there might be some plugins that wouldn't want to use &lt;object&gt;.<br /></div></blockquote>Did I?<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>joedw wrote:</cite><br />You also hinted at better cross-browser operation with &lt;embed&gt;. My examples don't show that, but the landscape changes with each update so I will check more.<br /></div></blockquote>It was certainly the case a few years ago (around 2005). If object works better now, then that's great.<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>joedw wrote:</cite><br />I try to keep track because any W3C browser that has trouble with &lt;object&gt; has to be off the main list of usable tools. Fortunately I don't find them anymore<br />Likewise for any plugin that 'needed' &lt;embed&gt;. But I don't think there are any of those.<br /></div></blockquote>Ok.<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>joedw wrote:</cite><br />Are small footprint mobile browsers limited to &lt;embed&gt;?<br /></div></blockquote>Not that I know of.<br /><br /><br />To summarize, the reasons you want &lt;embed&gt; to be obsolete are<br