rs that sometimes are involved in &lt;embed&gt;.<br /></div></blockquote> <br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />I don't follow.<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />Then you are writing &lt;embed&gt; elements for very simple things that don't need any commands or parameters. Remember that long string of commands you may need to send? In &lt;object&gt; they are &lt;param&gt;s. In &lt;embed&gt; they are a quoted string li&gt;ke the old .open. Just mostly uneditable or at least difficult to deal with, that is all. <br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />&lt;img&gt; can also be handled by a straightforward restyling to &lt;object&gt; syntax. It doesn't follow that &lt;img&gt; or &lt;embed&gt; should be obsoleted.<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />Here we are discussing a live, scriptable object that may wish to use services via the DOM. &quot;Dead' elements don't count. Really, I don't think &lt;img&gt; has a place in this conversation. I brought it in because the old spec test mentioned it (now changed). <br /><br />You hinted that there might be some plugins that wouldn't want to use &lt;object&gt;. Are there any really? <br />You also hinted at better cross-browser operation with &lt;embed&gt;. My examples don't show that, but the landscape changes with each update so I will check more. I try to keep track because any W3C browser that has trouble with &lt;object&gt; has to be off the main list of usable tools. Fortunately I don't find them anymore<br />Likewise for any plugin that 'needed' &lt;embed&gt;. But I don't think there are any of those. <br /><br />Are small footprint mobile browsers limited to &lt;embed&gt;?<br /><br />Thank You and Best Regards, <br />Joe<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=508">joedw</a> — Wed Jun 24, 2009 5:11 pm</p><hr />
