<author><name><![CDATA[joedw]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-06-24T10:03:02+00:00</updated>
<id>https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=4029&amp;p=5031#p5031</id>
<link href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=4029&amp;p=5031#p5031"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[About the object tag]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=4029&amp;p=5031#p5031"><![CDATA[
joedw wrote:<br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />With the current spec, would it make long term sense to: <br /><br />1. Obsolete using &lt;embed&gt;, especially as a fallback for &lt;object&gt;.<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />zcorpan wrote:<br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />Why?<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />Sorry slow getting back here, but so many whys ...<br /><br />&lt;embed&gt; should be obsoleted because this step would present an excellent way to discourage its use, especially as a fallback content container in an &lt;object&gt; element. <br />The only possible case for using &lt;embed&gt; is for old browsers that failed to implement &lt;object&gt; in a reasonable way. These include old browsers that ignored W3C totally concerning &lt;object&gt; and more recently old browsers that knew about &lt;object&gt; but would actually fail if they encountered @classid. In the first category, authors that support NS4 would then see that NS4 or earlier is the only use for &lt;embed&gt;, and authors targeting the second category could see that it is no longer necessary to worry, because recent and current latest versions of everything else are OK. <br /><br />joedw wrote:<br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />&quot;4.9.6 Page load processing model for content that uses plugins <br />... <br />When a resource that requires an external resource...<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />zcorpan wrote:<br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />It seems this is fixed already. Are you reading the Editor's draft or an older version?<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />Now I see it in:<br />&quot;6.11.6 Page load processing model for content that uses plugins<br />...and set the src attribute of the embed element to the address of the resource. &quot;<br /><br />That looks fine, except, <br /><br />joedw wrote:<br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />and I think embed could be dropped and use object instead for this.<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />zcorpan wrote:<br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />Why?<br /></div></blockquote> <br /><br />Because &lt;embed&gt; is really obsolete. If an author is told about the actual very limited subset of browsers that are out there that need &lt;embed&gt; then the author would probably not use it. Also, although it is traditional to use that autogenerated &lt;embed&gt; element to open a new context there is very little chance that a the user will be using a browser that needs &lt;embed&gt; for this case (usually clicking a link with a recognized file extension). <br /><br />So once again, &lt;embed&gt; is obsolete for every case except the the very limited subset of all browsers currently out there. <br /><br />I think another great reason to obsolet &lt;embed&gt; is that it is the last remnant of the long string of pairs that sometimes are involved in &lt;embed&gt;.  The other use was in the feature string of .open and that has now been dropped, and in fact ignored, as I last saw it. While ignoring this string is probably not the best idea for &lt;embed&gt; it is simple to recode using &lt;param&gt;s instead.<br /><br />And, if &lt;embed&gt; is gone from this usage, then some poor novice won't view source on the thing and see the obsolete use of &lt;embed&gt; in the autogenerated code and think that is the good path. <br /><br />Finally, any use of embed can be handled by a straighforward restyling to &lt;object&gt; syntax with &lt;param&gt;s. Although some plugins are tuned for &lt;embed&gt; and vice-versa, no existing plugins will be excluded by not encouraging embed. And if there are, well then the author would know it and it would be OK because even though it is 'officially' obsolete, &lt;embed&gt; will probably be supported. <br /><br />I don't really have anything to grind about obsoleting this what is arguably a maybe the last artifact of the GBWs, but the worst thing that could happen is I get introduced to some current tools that actually need &lt;embed&gt;. <br /><br />Thanks and Best Regards, <br />Joe<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=508">joedw</a> — Wed Jun 24, 2009 10:03 am</p><hr />
